    {
      "id": "K0KEkqkv5k4zeb7ELvw4F",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 2361.4274571695696,
      "y": 1285.4235128406037,
      "width": 756.9431762695312,
      "height": 540,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b0f",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1471195836,
      "version": 1385,
      "versionNonce": 1499128252,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1780130060548,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "2) Are we protecting customer's sensitive info like card details / password ?\n\nNaive way to just fill in the details on a form given by the Merchant server and then they\nsend it to us. This is obviously insecure. \n\nWe could also say that Merchant only receives\nthe details on the client before sending it to us and not on the server so maybe that is secure?\nHow do we enforce that? Even if it's achievable client can log it or store it somewhere.\n\n-----------------------\n\nTo bypass the Merchant completely, we can use iFrame -  a secure window on a webpage\nthat displays content from a completely different domain.\nSo, the Merchant's website is going to embed an iFrame which is from our domain\non which customers are going to fill the credit card details.\nWe will provide them a Javascript SDK.\n\nBrowsers also have same origin policy where Merchant's js code can't access\nour code even if they wanted to.\nFor more security, an additional layer of Asymmetric encryption (RSA) is given\nwith a public key, we encrypt data inside the iframe with this key and then we\ndecrypt the details using the private key.\n\n\n\n\n",
      "fontSize": 16,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "2) Are we protecting customer's sensitive info like card details / password ?\n\nNaive way to just fill in the details on a form given by the Merchant server and then they\nsend it to us. This is obviously insecure. \n\nWe could also say that Merchant only receives\nthe details on the client before sending it to us and not on the server so maybe that is secure?\nHow do we enforce that? Even if it's achievable client can log it or store it somewhere.\n\n-----------------------\n\nTo bypass the Merchant completely, we can use iFrame -  a secure window on a webpage\nthat displays content from a completely different domain.\nSo, the Merchant's website is going to embed an iFrame which is from our domain\non which customers are going to fill the credit card details.\nWe will provide them a Javascript SDK.\n\nBrowsers also have same origin policy where Merchant's js code can't access\nour code even if they wanted to.\nFor more security, an additional layer of Asymmetric encryption (RSA) is given\nwith a public key, we encrypt data inside the iframe with this key and then we\ndecrypt the details using the private key.\n\n\n\n\n",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
